The paper discusses the application of a simplicity bias based on a natural but algorithmic distribution of mutations in various examples, particularly binary matrices, to compare evolutionary convergence rates. This suggests that the paper may belong to the sub-category of cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing), which deals with the study of neural networks and evolutionary algorithms. Additionally, the paper discusses the potential of inducing the method on problems of optimization, such as genetic algorithms, which suggests that it may also belong to the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also discusses the evolution of modularity and genetic memory, which suggests that it may belong to the sub-category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) or cs.SY (Systems and Control). Finally, the paper discusses the natural approach introduced here as a better approximation to biological evolution, which suggests that it may also belong to the sub-category of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms).
